This practical was developed using R version 4.1.1.

Introduction

You perform a cohort study on annual influenza vaccine effectiveness. The aim of the study is to assess whether annual influenza vaccination reduces the risk of hospitalisation. The data consist of observations on eligible subjects who did, or did not, receive the annual influenza vaccine. The endpoint in this study is hospitalisation during the influenza epidemic period. Note that the vaccine was not randomly allocated; rather vaccination status may depend on characteristics of the participants in the study.

Variable Description Coding Meaning
vacc Influenza vaccination 0 Unvaccinated
vacc Influenza vaccination 1 Vaccinated
age Age Continuous Years
sex Sex 0 Male
sex Sex 1 Female
cvd Cardiovascular disease 0 Absent
cvd Cardiovascular disease 1 Present
pulm Pulmonary disease 0 Absent
pulm Pulmonary disease 1 Present
DM Diabetus mellitus 0 Absent
DM Diabetus mellitus 1 Present
contact Number of GP contacts Discrete Count
hosp Hospitalisation status 0 No hospitalisation
hosp Hospitalisation status 1 Hospitalisation

Aim of the practical

The aims of the current practical are:

  • to get familiar with inspecting and changing the imputation model in mice
  • to know how to report how missing data were handled

Preparation

The research question you will address here is whether influenza vaccination affects hospitalisation. As vaccination was not randomized, confounder adjustment is necessary. To investigate the effect of influenza vaccination on risk of hospitalisation, we will fit the following regression model:

formula(hosp ~ vacc + DM + cvd + pulm + I(log(contact)) + age + sex)

For missing data descriptives and default use of mice, consult your results for the past two practicals.

MICE - in-depth information

First, load the data with missing observations.

load("miss.data.multi.RData") # if the data is in your working directory
load(file.choose()) # if it is not

So far, we have configured MICE to decide by itself how to impute each variable with missing values. We will now have a brief look at some of the other options that can be tuned in MICE. As background reading, you may consult:
https://stefvanbuuren.name/fimd/sec-choices.html
https://stefvanbuuren.name/fimd/sec-modelform.html
https://stefvanbuuren.name/fimd/sec-knowledge.html

Day 3 and 4 will continue on more advanced aspects of multiple imputation.

As indicated, all binary variables have been imputed using logistic regression whereas missing values for contact have been imputed using predictive mean matching. We will now specify our own imputation method for this variable, and adopt linear regression for imputing log(contact):

MICE.data <- with(miss.data.multi, data.frame(sex = factor(sex), 
                                              age = age, 
                                              vacc = factor(vacc), 
                                              cvd = factor(cvd), 
                                              pulm = factor(pulm), 
                                              DM = factor(DM), 
                                              contact = contact,
                                              log.contact = log(contact), 
                                              hosp = factor(hosp)))

Note that we now have 2 variables contact and log.contact for the number of GP contacts. In order to ensure that mice() does not impute these variables twice, it needs to be informed about their relation. This can be achieved by means of passive imputation. Briefly, passive imputation can be used to ensure that a data transform always depends on the most recently generated imputations. Here, we will use passive imputation to ensure that imputed values for contact are obtained via log.contact (which is imputed via linear regression).

Recall that performing a dry run in mice() generates an empty multiply imputed data set with information on the imputation procedure.

# Configuration of the MICE model
MICE.0 <- mice(MICE.data, maxit = 0)
MICE.0
## Class: mids
## Number of multiple imputations:  5 
## Imputation methods:
##         sex         age        vacc         cvd        pulm          DM 
##          ""          ""    "logreg"    "logreg"    "logreg"    "logreg" 
##     contact log.contact        hosp 
##       "pmm"       "pmm"    "logreg" 
## PredictorMatrix:
##      sex age vacc cvd pulm DM contact log.contact hosp
## sex    0   1    1   1    1  1       1           1    1
## age    1   0    1   1    1  1       1           1    1
## vacc   1   1    0   1    1  1       1           1    1
## cvd    1   1    1   0    1  1       1           1    1
## pulm   1   1    1   1    0  1       1           1    1
## DM     1   1    1   1    1  0       1           1    1

We will now modify the imputation procedure to impute log-transformed values of contact using linear regression. First, we need to modify the predictor matrix to indicate that we will impute via the variable log.contact rather than via contact.

Each variable in our data set MICE.data has a row and a column in the predictor matrix. A value of 1 indicates that the column variable was used to impute missing values for the row variable. For example, the 1 at entry [vacc, sex] indicates that variable sex was used to impute the incomplete variable vacc. Note that the diagonal is zero because a variable is not allowed to impute itself. The row of sex contains all zeros because there were no missing values in sex. We can modify the predictor matrix to specify which variables should be used for imputation:

# Ensure that 'contact' is no longer used for generating imputations
pred <- MICE.0$predictorMatrix
pred[,"contact"] <- 0

We have now specified that the variable contact should no longer be used for imputation. The next step is to specify that we want to impute log.contact via linear regression:

method <- MICE.0$method
method["log.contact"] <- "norm"

Finally, we need to specify the relation between contact and log.contact, so that we can directly obtain imputed values for contact via log.contact:

# Declare that contact = exp(log.contact)
method["contact"] <- "~I(exp(log.contact))"

We can now start the imputation procedure:

# Start the imputation
MICE.imp.data.regress <- mice(MICE.data, method = method, pred = pred, print = F)
plot(MICE.imp.data.regress, y="log.contact", layout=c(2,1))

Again, we can estimate the adjusted odds ratio for influenza vaccination in the imputed datasets:

# Start the analyses
MIversion2 <- with(data = MICE.imp.data.regress, exp = glm(hosp ~ vacc + DM + cvd + pulm + I(log(contact)) + age + sex, family = binomial()))

# Use Rubin's rules
pooledEst <- pool(MIversion2)

Question 1. Interpret MICE.imp.data.default and MICE.imp.data.regress. Which method would you prefer for imputing binary and continuous variables?

Question 2 (Bonus). Assess the influence of adjusting the number of multiple imputations and/or the number of iterations. How many imputation and iterations do you think we need?

Reporting of missing data analysis

In your future work as a data scientist you may often be asked to perform an analysis for a colleague or client. This colleague would need information on how the analysis is performed.
Select one approach to handling missing data performed during the practicals in the past three weeks and describe it as if you would report back to a colleague (who is interested in fully understanding what you did :)). Use the part of the TRIPOD statement that addresses handling of missing data: https://www.acpjournals.org/doi/10.7326/M14-0698?articleid=2088542
